prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Group 1: 1.3mm continuum
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Observation of 6 embedded clusters in 1mm continuum (total 7 pointings), 0.3" ang. resolution, main 12-m array + ACA. Sensitivity of 0.1mJy/beam.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
THE TECHNICAL JUSTIFICATION FOR GROUP 1 AND 2 IS IDENTICAL. EACH GROUP SHARES CALIBRATORS WITHIN 10 DEG.
Sensitivity and angular resolution: At limiting cold and very dense initial conditions of 10K and n_H2 = 10^17 gcm^-3, the Jeans length and mass are 2500AU and ~0.5Msun. We request an angular resolution of 1000AU to adequately resolve the Jeans scale. At 3.31kpc, the furthest cluster in the sample, the Jeans length corresponds to our required resolution of 0.3.
Taking an opacity of 0.7 cm^2/g and a temperature of 20K (providing a lower limit) at 1.3mm, we obtain a corresponding integrated flux of 1.6mJy for the farthest object in the sample. Assuming the emission fragments on the Jeans scale, i.e. 2500AU or 0.76 at 3.31kpc, we expect a peak flux of ~0.5mJy/beam, accounting for the fact the emission will likely not be uniform but will be peaked. Thus to detect this 1.3mm emission with a S/N of 5, we request a sensitivity of 0.1 mJy/beam. With a bandwidth of 7.5GHz at 1.3mm this corresponds to 2min on source per cluster. As 2min is the minimum time on source, we have slightly adjusted our sensitivity in science goal Group 2 to 0.097mJy to meet this requirement. For 6 sources (7 pointings) in Group one the total requested time plus standard calibration and overheads is 2.54h and for 7 sources in Group 2 the total time is 2.56h, giving a total of 5.1h requested.
All of our selected clusters have bright associated emission in ATLASGAL at 870 microns on order of 1Jy/beam. To account for the difference in flux between 870 micron and 1.3mm we reduce the flux by nu^4, i.e. a factor of ~5. As the beam size of APEX is 19.2 at this frequency, the expected peak fluxes are likely on order 1-10mJy/beam, again taking into account the dust emission will have a filling factor of ~10% within the ATLASGAL beam. This estimated flux is in agreement with the peak fluxes of cores measured in similar mass clumps at similar resolution (Palau et al. 2013 and references within), which are also 1-10mJy/beam.
Choice of frequency: We specifically chose to centre our observations at 1.3mm (central sky freq. 233 GHz, representative freq. 242GHz, standard band 6) because the combination of ISM-like dust emission and the continuum sensitivity at different bands produces a signal-to-noise which levels off above Band 6. In addition, we also want to cover a reasonable area of the central regions of each cluster with one pointing. While the field of view increases at lower frequencies, Band 3 at 3mm would not be optimal, as we would expect strong free-free continuum from several of the most massive embedded stars in each cluster, biasing our core mass measurements. Therefore observing the dense gas in Band 6 at 1.3mm continuum produces a happy medium between these considerations.
Imaging Requirements: Our 12m-array and ACA observations will trace core scales from 0.3 to ~17 or 56,000AU at 3.31kpc. In addition, we will combine our data with the 870micron ATLASGAL data scaled to 1.3mm, and use it as a model for cleaning or using the feather task in CASA to recover the continuum emission on all scales. Flux recovery is especially important when studying the fragmentation properties of the cloud and constructing mass functions.
Table 1 of the scientific justification gives the cluster diameters. The size of the primary beam of the main array is 26, and for the ACA antennas it is 44, thus we will be able to cover the central dense regions of these clusters where most cores are expected to lie. In one case, marked with an * in the diameter column of Table 1, we have covered one cluster with several centres of star formation with two fields. We expect the brightest sources to lie inside the inner 1/3 of the primary beam and thus not effect the image quality.
Cluster group track sharing: To save calibration overheads, we have chosen two groups of clusters in which the clusters lie within 10 degrees of one another so they can share calibrators.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Understanding massive star formation requires a statistically significant study of their birth sites: embedded clusters. We request observations of 13 embedded clusters in 1.3mm continuum emission to determine their fragmentation and clustering properties. With these data we will investigate whether the clustering properties seen in the optical and IR are imprinted upon clusters at birth. Previous studies of cluster-forming and IR dark regions in the (sub-)mm have been hampered by small samples, lack of uv-coverage, missing flux and poor dynamic range. However, our proposed 12-m array + ACA observations will resolve below the Jeans length and mass AND recover all flux in the region when combined with ATLASGAL data. We aim to: investigate clustering statistics of the observed cores and their mass function and whether they depend on environment, compare the mm and IR clustering properties, and look for trends over cluster age. These results will not only solve important questions in the formation of clusters and high-mass stars, but will also profoundly affect how we interpret the properties of unresolved young massive star populations which dominate the luminosity of other galaxies.
